{{confuse|Hasse diagram}} [[Image:Hess diagram.jpg|thumb|Hess diagram with data from [[Sloan Digital Sky Survey|SDSS]] [[Galactic latitude|b]]>80 degree]] A '''Hess diagram''' plots the relative [[density]] of occurrence of [[star]]s at differing [[Color–magnitude diagram|color–magnitude]] positions of the [[Hertzsprung–Russell diagram]] for a given [[galaxy]] or resolved stellar population. The diagram is named after [[R. Hess]] who originated it in 1924.<ref>{{cite book| author = R. Hess (Heß) | date = 1924 | page = 265 | chapter = Die Verteilungsfunktion der absoluten Helligkeiten in ihrer Abhängigkeit vom Spektrum | title = Probleme der Astronomie. Festschrift fur Hugo v. Seeliger | publisher = Springer, Berlin}}</ref> Its use dates back to at least 1948.<ref name="Gaposchkin1948">{{cite journal | author=Gaposchkin, Cecilia Payne | title=The connection of motion with intrinsic variability. | journal=Astronomical Journal | date=1948 | volume=53 | pages=193 | bibcode=1948AJ.....53..193G | doi=10.1086/106093 }}</ref>
Hess diagrams are widely used in the study of discrete resolved stellar systems in and around the [[Milky Way]]. Specifically, in the analysis of [[Globular cluster|globular clusters]], [[Satellite galaxy|satellite galaxies]], and [[List of stellar streams|stellar streams]].
==See also== *[[Color-color diagram]]
